Phishing is a type of cybercrime where attackers trick users into sharing sensitive information such as passwords, OTPs, or bank details by pretending to be a trusted source.

A common example is when a student receives an email claiming to offer a paid internship. The email looks professional and creates urgency, asking the user to click a link and fill in personal details. Without verifying the sender, the student submits the form, including login credentials.

Later, the student notices suspicious activity such as unauthorized logins and password reset alerts. This happens because the attacker used the stolen information to access the account.

Phishing usually targets students and beginners who may not verify links carefully. The consequences include data theft, financial loss, and misuse of personal information.

This case highlights the importance of awareness and careful behavior while interacting online.
